(43, 2, 1, 43, 4, 46, 46, 'Cana of Galilee', 'Connection through Cana of Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Cana of Galilee as a significant location in Jesus'' ministry. The first passage introduces the setting of the wedding, while the second references Jesus'' return to Cana, linking the two events.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 1, 20, 31, 10, 12, 'marriage in Cana of Galilee', 'Marriage and Virtuous Woman', 'This connection highlights the theme of marriage, as both passages reference the significance of a marital relationship. John 2:1 introduces a marriage, while Proverbs 31:10-12 describes the qualities of a virtuous woman, essential for a successful marriage.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 1, 43, 21, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection through Cana in Galilee', 'Both passages emphasize Cana in Galilee, linking the wedding event in John 2:1 to Nathanael''s identity in John 21:2. This connection highlights the significance of this location in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 1, 20, 18, 22, 22, 'marriage in Cana of Galilee', 'Marriage and Favor from God', 'This connection highlights the theme of marriage as a significant event in both passages. John 2:1 introduces a marriage, while Proverbs 18:22 emphasizes finding a wife as obtaining favor from the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 1, 40, 12, 46, 46, 'mother of Jesus was there', 'Family Relationships in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Jesus'' mother, highlighting her role in his life. The mention of family in both contexts suggests a thematic connection regarding familial relationships and their significance in Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 1, 1, 2, 18, 25, 'marriage in Cana of Galilee', 'Marriage and Companionship Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of companionship and marriage. In John 2:1, the marriage at Cana signifies the joy and importance of union, paralleling Genesis 2:18-25, which describes the creation of woman as a companion for man.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 1, 19, 128, 1, 4, 'marriage in Cana of Galilee', 'Marriage and Blessing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of marriage and familial blessings. Both passages emphasize the joy and fulfillment found in relationships, with John 2:1 introducing a marriage and Psalms 128:3 describing a fruitful wife and happy children.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 2, 40, 10, 40, 42, 'Jesus was called', 'Reception and Invitation Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of invitation and acceptance. In John 2:2, Jesus and his disciples are invited to a marriage, while Matthew 10:40-42 emphasizes receiving those sent by Jesus, linking the act of welcoming with divine reward.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 2, 43, 1, 40, 49, 'Jesus was called', 'Invitation to Follow Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the calling of individuals to follow Jesus. In John 2:2, Jesus is invited to a marriage, while in John 1:40-49, disciples are called to follow Him. This connection highlights the theme of invitation and discipleship.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 2, 46, 7, 39, 39, 'marriage', 'Marriage and Freedom in Christ', 'This connection highlights the theme of marriage in both passages. John 2:2 mentions a marriage event, while 1 Corinthians 7:39 discusses the conditions under which a wife may remarry, emphasizing the significance of marital bonds.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 2, 51, 3, 17, 17, 'Jesus was called', 'Connection of Actions in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of actions done in the name of Jesus. John 2:2 shows Jesus participating in a communal event, while Colossians 3:17 encourages believers to act in His name.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 2, 58, 13, 4, 4, 'marriage', 'Marriage and Its Honor', 'This connection highlights the significance of marriage in both passages. John 2:2 presents Jesus at a marriage, while Hebrews 13:4 emphasizes the honor of marriage and the consequences of immorality.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 2, 40, 12, 19, 19, 'Jesus was called', 'Invitation and Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of being called to a gathering, as seen in both passages. In John 2:2, Jesus and his disciples are invited to a marriage, while Matthew 12:19 emphasizes a quiet demeanor, suggesting a response to a call without public display.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 2, 42, 7, 34, 38, 'Jesus was called, and his disciples', 'Jesus and Meals', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' presence at meals, highlighting his interactions with various social groups. In John, he is called to a marriage, while in Luke, he is invited to a Pharisee''s house, illustrating his role in communal gatherings.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 3, 19, 104, 15, 15, 'wine', 'Connection of Wine and Joy', 'This connection highlights the significance of wine in both passages, where wine is associated with joy and gladness. In John 2:3, the absence of wine at the wedding signifies a lack of joy, while Psalms 104:15 emphasizes wine as something that ''maketh glad the heart of man.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 3, 50, 4, 6, 6, 'They have no wine', 'Requesting Help in Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of presenting needs. In John 2:3, Mary identifies a lack of wine, while Philippians 4:6 encourages believers to make their requests known to God. Both passages emphasize the importance of acknowledging needs and seeking assistance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 3, 21, 10, 19, 19, 'They have no wine', 'Connection of Wine and Joy', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of wine in creating joy and merriment during feasts. In John 2:3, the absence of wine at a celebration prompts concern, while Ecclesiastes 10:19 highlights wine''s role in making merry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 3, 23, 24, 11, 11, 'They have no wine', 'Crying for Wine Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of a lack of wine, which symbolizes joy and celebration. Both passages emphasize the absence of wine and its impact on joy and mirth.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 3, 40, 26, 28, 28, 'They have no wine', 'Wine and Blood Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of wine as a symbol of transformation. In John 2:3, the absence of wine signifies a need, while in Matthew 26:28, wine represents the blood of the new covenant for the remission of sins.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 3, 43, 11, 3, 3, NULL, 'Concern for Needs', 'Both passages emphasize a sense of urgency regarding a need. In John 2:3, Mary expresses concern over the lack of wine, while in John 11:3, the sisters communicate their urgent need for Jesus'' help due to their brother''s illness.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 4, 43, 7, 6, 6, 'mine hour is not yet come', 'Connection of Jesus'' Timing', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of Jesus'' timing. In John 2:4, Jesus states, ''mine hour is not yet come,'' and in John 7:6, He reiterates, ''my time is not yet come,'' highlighting a consistent theme regarding the timing of His actions.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 4, 43, 7, 30, 30, 'mine hour is not yet come', 'Connection of Jesus'' Hour', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''hour'' in relation to Jesus'' actions. In John 2:4, Jesus indicates that his ''hour is not yet come,'' while in John 7:30, it is stated again that his ''hour was not yet come,'' highlighting a significant theme of timing in his ministry.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 4, 21, 3, 1, 1, 'mine hour is not yet come', 'Connection of Timing and Purpose', 'This connection highlights the theme of timing in both passages. Jesus indicates that there is a specific time for his actions, paralleling the idea in Ecclesiastes that there is a time for every purpose.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 4, 40, 8, 29, 29, NULL, 'Connection of Authority and Timing', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''what have we to do with thee,'' indicating a recognition of Jesus'' authority. Additionally, they reflect a concern about timing, with John noting ''mine hour is not yet come'' and Matthew referencing a specific time for torment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 4, 10, 16, 10, 10, 'What have I to do with thee?', 'Connection of Authority and Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in both passages. In John 2:4, Jesus'' response indicates a separation from immediate familial expectations, while in 2 Samuel 16:10, David expresses a similar detachment from the actions of others, emphasizing his acceptance of divine will.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 4, 10, 19, 22, 22, 'what have I to do with thee', 'Authority and Timing in Leadership', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority and the timing of actions in leadership. Both Jesus and David assert their positions and the appropriateness of their responses to those around them, emphasizing their control over the situation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 4, 5, 33, 9, 9, NULL, 'Family Relationships and Covenant', 'This connection highlights the theme of familial relationships and obligations. In both passages, there is a tension between personal ties and a greater commitment to divine purpose or covenant.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 5, 1, 6, 22, 22, 'Whatsoever he saith unto you, do it.', 'Obedience to Divine Instruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience in both passages. In John 2:5, Mary instructs the servants to follow Jesus'' commands, paralleling Noah''s adherence to God''s commands in Genesis 6:22.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 5, 43, 15, 14, 14, 'whatsoever he saith unto you', 'Obedience to Commands', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience in both passages. In John 2:5, Mary instructs the servants to do whatever Jesus says, paralleling John 15:14, where Jesus states that friendship is contingent upon doing His commands.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 2, 5, 58, 11, 8, 8, 'Whatsoever he saith unto you, do it', 'Obedience in Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience in both passages. Mary instructs the servants to do whatever Jesus says, paralleling Abraham''s obedience to God''s call without knowing the outcome.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
